<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><channel><title>Misc on Script Adults</title><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/categories/misc/</link><description>Recent content in Misc on Script Adults</description><image><title>Script Adults</title><url>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/images/papermod-cover.png</url><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/images/papermod-cover.png</link></image><generator>Hugo -- 0.140.0</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 28 Jun 2026 14:44:41 +0800</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://katsuragicsl.github.io/categories/misc/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Even a chinchilla is better than you in language learning</title><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/misc/even-a-chinchilla-is-better-than-you-in-language-learning/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Jun 2026 02:50:34 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/misc/even-a-chinchilla-is-better-than-you-in-language-learning/</guid><description>&lt;p>Ok it is definitely a clickbait. But as a native speaker of a language (Cantonese, Hong Kong/GuangZhou dialect) that does not have voicing constracts in its consonants, I had a real hard time in differentiate voiced and voiceless consonants when I started learning Japanese (which has the voicing constracts, and the voiceless consonants are unaspirated in native speakers&amp;rsquo; mouths most of the time).&lt;/p>
&lt;p>It was &amp;gt;10 years ago and I still remember how many times I listened and pronounced voiced and voiceless consonants with a Praat installed in my computer, and looked at the spectrograms allllll day long.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>The overthinking of LLM</title><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/misc/the-overthinking-of-llm/</link><pubDate>Mon, 10 Nov 2025 17:08:21 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/misc/the-overthinking-of-llm/</guid><description>&lt;p>I asked Deepseek to draw the Schlegel diagram of a hexahedron &amp;mdash; should be a very simple task right? Just 2 squares and link up their vertices. And yet I noticed something interesting: it tends to overthink and end up outputting nonsense answers when &lt;code>DeepThink&lt;/code> is on (which is supposed to be more powerful and &amp;ldquo;clever&amp;rdquo;), but getting the task done correctly when &lt;code>DeepThink&lt;/code> is off. Huh.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>So this is the prompt I gave Deepseek:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Most hilarious exercise I have seen so far</title><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/misc/most-hilarious-exercise/</link><pubDate>Fri, 08 Aug 2025 23:15:56 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/misc/most-hilarious-exercise/</guid><description>&lt;p>&lt;img loading="lazy" src="https://katsuragicsl.github.io/most-hilarious-exercise/vlad.png" alt="" />
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>That&amp;rsquo;s why I love Arnold&amp;rsquo;s books.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>[Updated 20250408]RISC-V explainer</title><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/misc/riscv-explainer/</link><pubDate>Mon, 31 Mar 2025 23:38:48 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/misc/riscv-explainer/</guid><description>&lt;style type="text/css">
